ng marriage. And yet we know very little about this new "normal" in romantic life. When do people decide to move in together, why do they do so, and what happens to them over time? Drawing on in-depth interviews, Sharon Sassler and Amanda Jayne Miller provide an inside view of how cohabiting relationships play out before and after couples move in together, using couples' stories to explore the he said/she said of romantic dynamics. Delving into hot-button issues, such as housework, birth control, finances, and expectations for the future, Sassler and Miller deliver surprising insights about the impact of class and education on how relationships unfold. Showcasing the words, thoughts, and conflicts of the couples themselves, Cohabitation Nation offers a riveting and sometimes counterintuitive look at the way we live now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aUnmarried couples - United States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aMiller, Amanda, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520962101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520962101.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles